@node Multiply.Extrude "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@prev Multiply.Extrude
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Extrude


            This is used to create three dimensional extrusions from two
        dimensional objects. Both ends of the newly created object will
        be exact replicas of the original two dimensional object. This is
        done by selecting the polygon or object face to be extruded and
        resizing its depth in the other two planar views. The object or
        polygon to be extruded must be contained within the bounding box
        in the primary planar view (selected with the mouse). The depth
        may be modified by moving the "T" shaped handle in either of the
        other two planar views. When satisfied with the extrusion, press
        the Make command.

            @{"     " link Multiply.Make        } Multiply - Make
            @{"     " link Multiply.Path_Extrude} Multiply - Path Extrude
            @{"     " link Multiply.Rail_Extrude} Multiply - Rail Extrude
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Extrude   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Lathe "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Lathe


            This is used to create three dimensional extrusions in a
        cylindrical shape from an object, polygon, or group of points.
        This allows the selected group to be spun about a central axis,
        and creates objects such as drinking glasses, vases, and similar
        objects. Only one cross section needs to be designed, and the
        others are replicated about the specified axis. To lathe a group,
        select the central axis in one of the planar views using the
        left mouse button. This will be represented by a crosshair in the
        current planar view, and as a line in either of the other two
        planar views. The object will be spun around the crosshair using
        the Make command.

            @{"     " link Multiply.Make        } Multiply - Make
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Crosshair   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Lathe   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Mirror "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Mirror


            This is used to create a mirror image of the selected objects
        or points in the current layer. The axis where the actual mirror
        appears will be displayed in two planar views either by a vertical
        or horizontal line. If the axis passes through the selected group,
        the mirrored object will intersect with the original object. When
        satisfied with an axis for mirroring, press the Make command.

            @{"     " link Multiply.Make        } Multiply - Make

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Numeric "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Numeric


            This is used to alter precise values regarding the size and
        location of the selected objects. This is also used to modify
        other values that are unique to the given objects or commands.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Make "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Make


            This option is used to actually create the object designed
        with the Multiply tools. Lightwave allows the user to modify the
        exact specifications of the new objects without actually creating
        the object. For example, to form a mirror, the user would drag the
        axis of the mirror on the editing window. This mirror may have
        its position altered by clicking the mouse where desired. The Make
        button would be used to actually define the points and polygons
        needed for the new object.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Bevel "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Bevel


            This is used to create a bevel around a polygon or group of
        polygons. Each polygon is shifted along an axis similar to an
        extrusion. However, the extruded face may be resized using the
        inset parameter, which creates the actual bevel. This command
        will open a requester where the shift and inset values may be
        entered.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 497 242 pictures/pic.multiply.bevel Bevel'"} ILBM: Bevel
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.B} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Bevel       @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Extrude     @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Sm_Shift "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Smooth Shift


            This is used to create clones of selected polygons
        perpendicular to their normals. A polygon such as a sqaure,
        when operated on, would have a second similar polygon created
        with similar shape yet a possible difference in size.

            Smooth Shifting a box would cause 6 new sides to appear as
        if they had exploded from the original box and began to travel
        a uniform distance away from the box.

            Smooth shifting a sphere would cause all of the polygons
        to create a new sphere encompassing the first, since the new
        polygons have been created uniformly from the originals.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 427 253 pictures/pic.multiply.smooth_shift.1 Smooth_Shift'"} ILBM: Smooth Shifted Box
            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 427 253 pictures/pic.multiply.smooth_shift.2 Smooth_Shift'"} ILBM: Smooth Shifted Sphere
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Clone        @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.N} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Normal       @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Path_Extrude "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Path Extrude


            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Extrude   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Path      @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Rail_Extrude "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Rail Extrude

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Extrude   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Patch "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Patch

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Skin "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@version 2.156
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Skin


            This is used to create a skin of polygons between two or more
        polygons. This skin will connect the polygons as if they had
        morphed from each other. For example, if a wire model were
        constructed, the skin would be stretched over the various wires
        to create the continuous outer layer. This is similar to a morph,
        yet morphing will create slices between polygons as well as the
        skin connecting the polygons. Skinned polygons do not have to be
        similar or have the same number of points.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 531 246 pictures/pic.multiply.skin Skin'"} ILBM: Skin
            @{"     " link Multiply.Skin                          } Multiply - Morph
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.S}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Skin   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Morph "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Morph


            This is used to create a morph between two polygons with the
        same number of points. The two selected polygons will be morphed
        based upon the ordering of their points when the polygons were
        created. In the event that the two polygons do not have their
        points ordered the same, morphed objects may appear to twist
        or alter size. The number of segments created may be specified.
        Each segment is an additional polygon placed within the newly
        created object.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 461 233 pictures/pic.multiply.morph Morph'"} ILBM: Morph
            @{"     " link Multiply.Skin                          } Multiply - Skin
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.M}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Morph   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Clone "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Clone


            This is used to produce identical copies of the selected
        objects or polygons. These clones may be resized and relocated
        using the Clone input requester. Cloned objects will have the
        same number of points, polygons, and edges as the original,
        and these parts will be ordered similarly in relation to
        themselves. Resizing the clones will alter the X, Y, and Z
        dimensions of the clones. Relocating it will position the clones
        in another location in the current layer.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 479 237 pictures/pic.multiply.clone Clone'"} ILBM: Clone
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Clone   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Array "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Array


            This is used to create a set of cloned objects in an arrayed
        pattern within the current layer. This array will clone the
        object three dimensionally, with clones appearing about each
        axis. The number of clones created on each dimension may be
        modified. This will produce arrayed clones in varying volumes.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 497 244 pictures/pic.multiply.array Array'"} ILBM: Array
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Array   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Clone   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Path_Clone "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Path Clone

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Clone     @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Path      @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Multiply.Rail_Clone "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@next Multiply.Rail_Clone
@toc Modeler.Multiply

    Multiply - Rail Clone

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Clone     @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.R }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Rail      @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Modeler.Polygon "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@prev Modeler.Multiply
@next Modeler.Tools
@toc Main

    Modeler - Polygon

        @{"     " link Polygon.Points       } Points
        @{"     " link Polygon.Make         } Make
        @{"     " link Polygon.Remove       } Remove
        @{"     " link Polygon.Add_Point    } Add Point
        @{"     " link Polygon.Remove_Point } Remove Point
        @{"     " link Polygon.Attach       } Attach
        @{"     " link Polygon.Detach       } Detach
        @{"     " link Polygon.Split        } Split
        @{"     " link Polygon.Merge        } Merge
        @{"     " link Polygon.Surface      } Surface
        @{"     " link Polygon.Triple       } Triple
        @{"     " link Polygon.Subdivide    } Subdivide
        @{"     " link Polygon.Align        } Align
        @{"     " link Polygon.Unify        } Unify
        @{"     " link Polygon.Flip         } Flip

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Points "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@prev Polygon.Points
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Points


            This is used to add single or multiple points to the current
        layer. The points are created one at a time at the current
        location of the crosshair. The left mouse button is used to
        locate where the next point will be created, while the right
        button is used to actually create the point at the current
        location. The Make command may also be used to create the point.
        The points, when created, will remain selected.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 427 253 pictures/pic.cube.point Point'"} ILBM: Point
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Point   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Make "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Make


            This is used to create a polygon from a group of selected
        points. The polygon will be ordered based on the order the
        points were selected. In some cases, polygon edges may overlap
        due to point ordering. To avoid this, ensure that the points
        are selected in the proper order, or use the Drag command to
        alter the shape of the polygon.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 427 253 pictures/pic.cube.point Point'"} ILBM: Point
            @{"     " link Modify.Drag                              } Modify - Drag
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Point     @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Polygon   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Remove "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Remove


            This is used to delete a polygon face without deleting the
        points about the perimeter of the polygon or selected polygons.
        The Cut command, located in the cut and paste menu, will remove
        both the polygon, the edges, and all the points attached to the
        polygon.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Cut             @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Cut and Paste   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.D}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Delete          @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Polygon         @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Add_Point "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Add Point


            This is uses to add points to an edge of a polygon. The edge
        will be connected to the new point by forming two new edges, and
        then completing the polygon face to match the newly added point.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 427 253 pictures/pic.cube.point Point'"} ILBM: Point
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Point   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Remove_Point "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Remove Point


            This is used to remove a point or points from a polygon
        without deleting the point from the current layer. The polygon
        will be modified to connect a new edge where the removed point
        originally was located.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 427 253 pictures/pic.cube.point Point'"} ILBM: Point
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Point   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Attach "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Attach

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Detach "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Detach

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Split "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Split


            This is used to divide a polygon into two polygons. This is
        done by selecting two points about the perimeter of the polygon
        that are not sharing an edge. The Split command will then add
        an edge between these two points and reconstruct the original
        polygon into two new polygons that share a common edge.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 410 183 pictures/pic.polygon.split Split'"} ILBM: Split
            @{"     " link Polygon.Subdivide} Polygon - Subdivide
            @{"     " link Polygon.Triangle } Polygon - Triangle
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Polygon    @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.T}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Triangle   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Merge "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Merge


            This is used to combine two polygons into a single polygon.
        The two polygons must share at least one edge to be merged. The
        resulting polygon will be the combination of the two polygons.
        Merging may remove an edge that was meant to be preserved.
        Merging may also be used on polygons that are identical and in
        the same location, which may occur frequently. Merged polygons
        will have less points, polygons, and edges than the unmerged
        polygons, in most cases.

            @{"     " link Polygon.Unify} Polygon - Unify
            @{"     " link Tools.Merge  } Tools - Merge

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Surface "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Surface


            This is used to specify the surface to be rendered on the
        selected polygon or polygons. This is normally done in the
        Layout editor, however it may also be done while objects are
        being modeled.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.S}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Surface   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Triple "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Triple


            This is used to convert a polygon into triangles. This is
        a more basic form of a polygon, where each triangular polygon
        contains only 3 edges and 3 points. Using triangles allows
        various rendering tricks and modeler functions to be much more
        accurate.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 480 249 pictures/pic.polygon.triple Triple'"} ILBM: Triple
            @{"     " link Polygon.Subdivide                      } Polygon - Subdivide
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Polygon    @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.T}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Triangle   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Subdivide "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Subdivide


            This is used to divide a triangle into additional triangles.
        This is done by calculating the midpoint of each edge and then
        connecting these midpoints as a newly created triangle. By doing
        so, rendering algorithms and modeler functions will be more
        accurate.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 483 245 pictures/pic.polygon.subdivide Subdivide'"} ILBM: Subdivide
            @{"     " link Polygon.Triple                         } Polygon - Triple
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Polygon    @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.T}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Triangle   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Align "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Align

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Unify "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Unify


            This is used to remove polygons that are sharing the same
        edges and points. Unlike Merge, the polygons must have the
        same points and edges with no exceptions. Removing duplicate
        polygons will decrease memory usage and rendering times, and
        will increase efficiency.

            @{"     " link Polygon.Merge} Polygon - Merge
            @{"     " link Tools.Merge} Tools - Merge

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Polygon.Flip "Lightwave 3D - Modeler"
@next Polygon.Flip
@toc Modeler.Polygon

    Polygon - Flip


            This is used to reverse the normal to the plane created by
        the selected polygon or polygons. The normal will determine
        which face will be rendered on single sided polygons, and
        determines the actual orientation of the polygon.

            @{"     " rxs "address command 'display.s 549 250 pictures/pic.polygon.flip Flip'"} ILBM: Flipped Polygon
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.N}@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Normal     @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P}@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Polygon    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


